Exploratory Reort on Juvenile Snowshoe Hares Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest

Matthew McCafferty

11/6/2021

1. Introduction

This report provides an overview of differences in juvenile Snowshoe Hare weight observed in the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest, Alaska observed from 1999-2011. Specifically, the relationship between sex and weight compared across the sites and the relationships between hind foot length and weight.

2. Data and Analysis

The Snowshoe Hare physical data was collected by Dr. Kieland and associates at the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest, Alaska from 1999-2011. The data contains 3197 observations of 14 variables over the course of 12 years at three different sites. Following exploratory data visualization, weight between male and female juvenile snowshoe hares are by two-sample t-tests using a significance level (α) of 0.05 throughout. Differences between groups are described by Cohen’s d effect size. The relationship between hind foot length and body weight is explored by simple linear regression. All analyses are in R version 4.0.2 using RStudio version 1.3.1056.

3. Juvenile Hare Initial Investigation

A. Annual juvenile hare trap counts.

Figure 1 Total number of juvenile Snowshoe Hares Trapped each year at the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest, Alaska (1999-2012).

The minimum value for Juvenile Snowshoe Hare annual trappings was 2 recorded in 2010, and a maximum value 126 recorded in 1999. The central tendency for annual juvenile trappings were 31.5 (mean) and 18.5 (median) with a standard deviation of 35.88. Overall, there is a lot of fluctuation between counts per year, with 1999 and 2000 being higher than any other year over the 12 year period. The counts could have been impacted by the number of days and number of traps per year. With some significant variations in counts per year, more trapping and environmental data need to be collected to understand variables that might affect juvenile Snowshoe Hare populations for future analyses.

B. Visualize juvenile hare weights.

Figure 2: Relationship between body weight (g) and gender of juvenile snowshoe hares observed in each study site within the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest between 199-2012.The box endpoints indicate the 25th and 75th percentile values; the black line and black point within the box indicate the median and mean value for each gender, respectively. The upper whiskers represent the maximum value and and the lower whisker represent the minimum values. Data: Keilland et al. (2017)

Overall, the median and mean juvenile body weights (g) were larger for males than females at all three sites. Male and Female body weights were the largest at the Bonanza Spruce site, with higher mean and median values compared to the other sites. The unknown gender represented in gray collected at the Bonanza Mature site has a similar mean weight to male weights collected at that site. The unknown genders collected at the Bonanza Riparian have significantly lower mean and median weights when compared to male and female weights; however, there are very few unknown samples at that site.

C. Juvenile weight comparison (male & female snowshoe hares).

Male 945.86 990 333.22 163

Table 1 Relationship between body weight (g) and sex of juvenile snowshoe hares observed within the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest, Alaska (1999-2012).

The body weight of juvenile snowshoe hares was compared between genders where sampling site was not considered in this comparison (but may need to be in the future for a more accurate assessment of weights between sites). A cohen.d() and and a Welch two-sample t.test() were run between male and female hare weights to determine the size and significance of gender on juvenile hare body weight. Exploratory plots revealed the data to be normally distributed. Mean weight for male hares (945.86 g) is 90.47 g (10.58%) larger than mean weight for female hares (855.39 g). As a result of the cohen.d() and t.test(), gender and body weight of juveniles are not closely related (Cohen’s d = 0.29) though they are statistically significant (Welch Two Sample t-test: p = 0.007). A p value of =0.007 suggests that there is a 0.71 percent chance that if our male and female hare populations were drawn from samples of the same mean, the sample means would be at least -90.47 g different.

D. Relationship between juvenile weight & hind foot length.

Figure 3 Relationship between Hindfoot length (mm) and weight (g) for the juvenile Snowshoe Hares at the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest. The points indicate individual juvenile Snowshoe hare measurements (gold circles). Linear model summary: β1 = 9.52 g mm-1, p < 0.001 0, R2 = 0.299, Pearson’s r = 0.55). Data: Kielland, K et al. (2017)

The relationship between body weight (g) and hind foot length (mm) appears to be linear (Figure 4). Simple linear regression revealed that hind foot length significantly predicts body weight (p < 0.001, R2 = 0.3) with an average slope of \(\beta\) = 9.52 g mm-1. For each one millimeter increase in hind foot length we expect on average an increase in body weight of 9.52. Hind foot length and body weight is positively correlated (Pearson’s r = -279.34, 9.52, p < 0.001). Experimental plots reveal normally distributed and homoscedastic residuals. One concern is not including gender in this figure. Since we are not incorporating gender into this analysis, there may be a relationship between gender and hindfoot length/weight not represented in the results.

4. Summary

Exploratory data analysis reveals the following initial findings:

  • On average juvenile body weights (g) were higher for male snowshoe hares than female snowshoe hares at all three sites
  • The Bonaza Spruce Site had the largest Male and female juvenile Snowshoe Hare body weights
  • Hind foot length (mm) and body weight (g) appear linearly related; the relationship (by simple linear regression) is significant, with a slope (expected average increase in body weight with a 1 mm increase in hind foot length) of 9.52 g mm-1.
